Basically a demilled kit that had its receiver welded back together.Advantage to this is you have an almost entirely original military issued AK. Not a commercial manufactured copy.Down side is that the welds show until refinshed.This particular version is in good surplus condition.Bluing is about 80% and no longer a deep color. There is scattered pitting, but no actively rusting spots. Bore is good/very good with strong rifling.Matching numbers and correctly configured early version M70.Milled receiver.I have two grips for it. title: For Sale:  DOUBLE BARREL, authentic, muzzle-loading SHOTGUN with DAMASCUS barrels
postcontent:
A family member passed this shotgun onto me in 1962, 56 years ago. My heirs won't know what to do with it, so I must sell it. It is all original. Contact me for more photos. It looks to be 12 gauge but Alcan made me 2 boxes (500 each) of 14 gauge wads that fit easily, enough to hold down powder and shot nicely. A 12 gauge wad jams in tightly in my opinion, deforming on the edges of a card-wad.
Locks are good & solid with hammers locking in definite, positive, solid clicks; box springs; stored in low humidity so the wood is absolutely solid; twisted Damascus 30" barrels, on top of the rib is stamped "F I N E    T W I S T"; under one barrel is stamped an "H" and " V I" under the other barrel. There is a tiny cartouche near the breechblock with an "F" "L" and "G" inside and the proof mark is symbolic. Top of the right barrel 8.5" from the muzzle, someone applied a spot of silver solder and polished it smooth. The inside of the barrel does not show this spot. Ramrod is solid with a very nice, reversible worm (corkscrew) on the end.
I cannot find a manufacturer name on it. In the late 1970's a supposed expert told me to tie it to an old tire and fire a double-charge out of it, which I did, but doing so broke the pistol grip, which I stuck back together with grey, industrial grade epoxy. In the photos one can see a line where some of the grey epoxy oozed out. The fix is very solid, but someone with young, steady hands needs to clean this line with a dental drill or dental tools. I fired it one time after that at some clay birds at a muzzle loading event and it won the event.

title: For Sale:  WWII 91/30 Sniper Scope for Mosin Nagant
location: South Oklahoma City, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
PU 91/30 Sniper Scope for a 91/30 Mosin Nagant Sniper Rifle. Manufactured between 1943-1944 in the Progress factory, Stamped 1943 as the production year accompanied by the following        Serial# A-51558
 
These Soviet Sniper Scopes are the last remaining items in the Russian Armory System (not still mounted to the rifles currently). The side rail is not included with the scope because it typically remained attached to the rifle after the scope was removed for storage purposes.
 
The scope comes with the original PU Mosin-Nagant Side Mount (Kochetov mount)  This scope is in excellent condition, especially when you consider its age and what it has seen along its journey. I think the exceptionally clear optics are simply amazing and one of its most sought-after features. Accompanying it when purchased is the original scope bag and the original leather lens covers as well. To wrap things up, the finish has maintained itself extremely well after all these years preserving the rich black color that makes this scope visually stunning.
